Full description
The most popular beaches of Zanzibar are in Nungwi. This is mostly because the tides do not have such a huge impact on the beach. 
But, did you know that Nungwi is also the capital of local dhow manufacturing? 
Find out all about how these impressive sailing vessels are made and get the chance to see local craftsmen in action.

Later, enjoy lunch in a local restaurant. 
After that, experience a real turtle sanctuary. Here, turtles are treated and healed of any illnesses before being released to the ocean.

New York is full of park benches. In fact, thereâs 9,000 in Central Park alone â and I like to think of each one as an extension of our already too small apartments. Theyâre the front row seat to witness the city unfold, a spot to rest tired feet from walking too many blocks, a refuge for the last few chapters of a really, delicious book when you donât want to take the subway home, not just yet. Itâs funny, but something so seemingly ordinary like a public park bench can actually be quite personal for a New Yorker. (I still pass the bench where I had an amazing first kiss with my boyfriend and without fail, it always makes me smile when I see it.)

Simply put, park benches are the talisman of New York memories â past, present and future â and when they have a dedication plaque on them? Oh, theyâre magical! Yours truly has spent many weekend afternoons wandering and reading different plaque dedications â itâs usually how I determine where Iâll ultimately sit, waiting for the right one to tug at my heartstrings. Each one makes me more and more curious about a story Iâll truthfully never know, like a sliver of a chapter of someone elseâs life. Over the years, Iâve read many favorites, in different parks around the city, but a recent highlight was finding a bench dedicated to John Lennon from Yoko Ono herself, in which she included the following quote from her late husband:

âEverything will be okay in the end. If itâs not okay, itâs not the end.â

Her sign off was a simple âSee you whenever. - yoko onoâ.

Sometimes when Iâm feeling a bit down or defeated, Iâll end up at that bench, for a much needed reminder. And Iâll sit, with no other intention than to watch the city go by. And similarly, I hope this can serve as your gentle reminder to romanticize the ordinary, small moments in your day, too. Yes, even something as simple as a park bench.

Save this two day Jaipur itinerary! ð¸

Day 1 Itinerary-
Morning - Visit City Palace. (Timings - 9am to 5pm | Price - INR 300 | Need 2-3 hours to tour)
- Optional - Visit Jantar Mantar - Right next to the City Palace, a great place for astronomy lovers. (Timings - 9 AM to 4.30 PM | Price - INR 50 | Need Max 1 hour for the tour)

Afternoon - Visit the Bapu Bazaar for some shopping & then have lunch in front of the Hawa Mahal - Visit The Tattoo Cafe & Lounge.

After lunch, head straight to Chokhi Dhani.
Evening -  Visit Chokhi Dhani - experience Rajasthani culture, art, food. (Timings - 5 PM to 11PM | Price : INR 900 | Need to 4 hours & Dinner is served here)

Day 2 Itinerary,
Early morning : Visit Jal Mahal for a beautiful sunrise, It gets crowded soon.

Morning : Visit the Amber Fort, DO NOT take the jeep service if you're comfortable walking up a few flights of stairs. (Timings: 8 AM to 5.30 PM | Price : INR 100 | need 3 to 4 hours max)
Panna Meena ka Kund is just 10 minutes walking from Amber fort if you want to visit.

Afternoon: Jaigarh Fort (Timings - 9 AM to 4:30 PM | Price - INR 35 | takes 1 hour to tour)

Evening - End the day watching a beautiful sunset at the Nahargarh Fort. (Timings : 10 AM to 10 PM | Price INR 50 | takes 2-3 hours)
